description: From 16th-century parsnepe, from Middle English passenep, a modification of Old French pasnaie by influence of Middle English nepe (“turnip”), from Latin pastināca (“parsnip, carrot”), from pastinum (“two-pronged fork”) as in pastināre (“to dig up the ground”).

entries.meaning: A biennial plant, Pastinaca sativa, related to the carrot.
The root of the parsnip, when used as a vegetable.
